b:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 mb-6 not-prose","children":["$","ul",null,{"className":"space-y-2.5 border-l-4 border-yellow-400/50 pl-4","children":[["$","li","0",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"Four botnets dismantled in coordinated operation"}]]}],["$","li","1",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"316,000 DDoS attacks traced to networks"}]]}],["$","li","2",{"className":"flex items-start gap-2.5 leading-snug","children":[["$","span",null,{"className":"mt-0.5 text-base flex-shrink-0 animate-pulse","style":{"color":"#f5c518","textShadow":"0 0 8px #f5c518, 0 0 18px #f5a500aa"},"children":"★"}],["$","span",null,{"className":"text-xl italic text-text-primary","children":"3 million devices freed from criminal control"}]]}]]}]}]
c:["$","div",null,{"className":"article-enter-delay-3 article-prose max-w-none","children":[["$","p",null,{"children":["The US Departments of Justice and Defense just pulled the plug on one of the largest botnet operations ever discovered. Four separate networks, controlling approximately 3 million compromised devices, were dismantled in a coordinated operation that represents a significant blow to global cybercrime infrastructure. Combined, these botnets were responsible for over ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.tomshardware.com/news/us-doj-dod-dismantle-botnets-3-million-devices","children":"316,000 DDoS attacks"}]," worldwide, according to ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.tomshardware.com/","children":"Tom's Hardware"}],".\nThe scale here matters. Three million devices isn't just a statistic—it's a distributed army capable of flooding targets with traffic, taking down websites, services, and critical infrastructure. That's roughly the population of a mid-sized country, all weaponized and pointing at targets the operators chose.\nFor everyday users, this takedown means potentially millions of ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.cisa.gov/news-events/news/securing-your-home-network","children":"routers and IoT devices"}]," are no longer silently participating in attacks. That sluggish smart home gadget? It might have been part of someone else's crime spree."]}],"\n",["$","div",null,{"className":"not-prose my-8 pt-6 border-t border-white/10","children":[null,["$","div",null,{"className":"glass-card overflow-hidden mb-4 !hover:transform-none","children":["$","img",null,{"src":"/images/articles/us-crushes-botnet-empire-spanning-3-million-device/subtitle.jpg","alt":"What this actually changes for the threat landscape","className":"w-full h-auto max-h-[400px] object-cover"}]}],["$","p",null,{"className":"text-text-secondary italic text-lg leading-relaxed font-medium","children":"What this actually changes for the threat landscape"}]]}],"\n",["$","p",null,{"children":["The operation signals something more interesting than a single victory. It shows US agencies are increasingly capable of not just responding to cyber threats, but proactively dismantling the infrastructure behind them. That's a shift from reactive to offensive posturing, and it changes the calculus for criminal organizations building these networks.\nThe botnet economy thrives on scale and anonymity. When agencies can coordinate takedowns of this magnitude across jurisdictions, the risk-reward ratio shifts. It doesn't eliminate the threat—new botnets will emerge—but it raises the operational cost for actors who've operated with relative impunity.\nThere's speculation these botnets may have facilitated activities beyond ",["$","a",null,{"href":"https://www.cloudflare.com/learning/ddos/what-is-a-ddos-attack/","children":"DDoS attacks"}],", potentially including credential theft or cryptocurrency mining. If confirmed, the ripple effects could be broader than initially apparent.\nPravi signal ovdje je demonstrating that infrastructure-scale cybercrime has become a targetable problem for nation-state agencies."]}]]}]
